# opencode-do Cloudflare Remote Server POC

Source: <https://github.com/southpolesteve/opencode-do>

## What it demonstrates

`opencode-do` is a proof-of-concept for running OpenCode's remote server API on Cloudflare Workers + Durable Objects, then connecting with:

```bash
opencode attach <worker-url>
opencode run --attach <worker-url> "..."
```

The useful shape:

```text
OpenCode CLI/TUI
  -> HTTP + SSE remote server API
  -> Cloudflare Worker router
  -> Session Durable Object
  -> Durable Object SQLite message persistence
  -> model call
```

## Source-grounded constraints

The README explicitly calls it a POC with these limits:

- rate limited demo
- no Read/Write/Edit/Bash tools
- no filesystem
- single Workers AI model in the demo
- no response streaming in the current POC

The README also points at possible extensions:

- `worker-fs-mount` with Durable Object, R2, or memory-backed filesystems
- Dynamic Worker Loaders / Cloudflare Agents SDK Codemode for isolated code execution
- `isomorphic-git` plus R2/DO storage for Git operations
- Cloudflare Containers for heavier shell/build/test workloads
- AI Gateway for stronger external models

## Why this matters for ShitRat

This is interesting less as production code and more as a protocol receipt: a coding-agent TUI can attach to a Cloudflare Durable Object session over HTTP/SSE, with state persisted in DO SQLite and the compute hibernating when idle.

For ShitRat, that suggests a Cloudflare-hosted session control plane could exist without a permanent local executor process, while privileged or heavyweight work remains separately sandboxed.
